{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}

'''James Kynvyn''' (second half 16th-early 17th century) was an English craftsman, active between 1569 and 1610.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mhs.ox.ac.uk/epact/maker.php?MakerID=70 | title=James Kynvyn | publisher=Museum of the History of Science | work=Epact | accessdate=22 June 2016}}</ref>

All that is known about him is that his workshop was located near [[St. Paul's Cathedral]] in [[London]]. He built high-quality mathematical instruments, notably [[graphometer]]s, [[compass]]es, and [[quadrant (instrument)|quadrants]].

