{{England-bio-stub}}

'''Jenny Greene''' (born October 9, 1978) is an Astrophysicist and Professor at [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/astro/people/faculty/jenny-greene/|title=Princeton University's Astronomy Faculty and Research Staff List|last=|first=|date=|website=Princeton University|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> She is notable for her work on [[supermassive black hole]]s and the galaxies in which they reside.
Greene got her B.S degree in 2000 from [[Yale University]], majoring in Astronomy and Physics. She then attended [[Harvard University|Harvard]] for her Ph.D in Astronomy, her thesis entitled ''The Growth of Black Holes: From Primordial Seeds to Local Demographics''.<ref>{{cite web|bibcode=2005AAS...20719703G|title=The Growth of Black Holes: From Primordial Seeds to Local Demographics|last=Greene|first=J.E.|last2=Ho|first2=L.C.|date=December 2005|website=adsabs.harvard.edu|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=14 June 2016}}</ref> After her post-doctoral fellowship at Princeton, she became an Assistant Professor of Astronomy at [[UT Austin]] for a year. Since 2011, she has been an Assistant Professor of Astrophysical Sciences at Princeton.
Her broad research interests include measurements of black hole masses, the connection between supermassive black holes and galaxies, stellar and gas kinematics of galactic nuclei, and diffuse light in galaxy clusters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.princeton.edu/main/news/archive/S42/79/15M34/index.xml?section=featured|title=Astrophysicist Greene studies the bright side of black holes|author=Zandonella|first=Catherine|date=2015-07-09|website=Princeton University|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
Greene serves on the Leadership Committee of the Prison Teaching Initiative at Princeton University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prisonteaching.org/leadership|title=PTI Leadership|last=|first=|date=|website=ptiweb|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>
== Awards and honors == * The [[Alfred P. Sloan Fellowship]] (2011) * The Bok Prize, [[Harvard University|Harvard]] Astronomy Department (2009) * [[Annie Jump Cannon Award in Astronomy|Annie Jump Cannon Award]], AAS (2008) * Carnegie-Princeton Fellow (2006–2010) * Hubble Fellow (2006–2009) * NSF Graduate Student Research Fellowship (2001–2003) * Certificate of Distinction in Teaching (2002–2003) * Summa Cum Laude, [[Yale University]] (2000) * George Beckwith Prize in Astronomy, [[Yale University]] (2000) * [[Phi Beta Kappa Society|Phi Beta Kappa]] (2000)
