{{Infobox planet | extrasolarplanet = yes | name = <!-- Displays on top of infobox--> | image = <!-- Use bare filename: Example.jpg --> | image_size = <!-- Overrides image size default of 225px --> | image_alt = | caption = | apsis = astron | discovery_ref = <!-- <ref>...</ref>--> | discovery = yes | discoverer = [[Scott S. Sheppard]] | discovered = 2018<!--(Date)--> | discovery_site = | discovery_method = | alt_names = <!--(Any alternative names for the body)--> | periastron = | apoastron = | semimajor = | avg_speed = <!--(Average orbital speed)--> | eccentricity = 0.094<ref name="ScottSS" /> | period = 252 days<ref name="ScottSS" /><!--(Orbital period)--> | inclination = 30.61&deg;<ref name="ScottSS" /> | angular_dist = | long_periastron = <!--(Longitude of periastron)--> | time_periastron = <!--(Time of periastron)--> | semi-amplitude = | mean_radius = <!--(For planets & large, spheroidal minor planets)--> | mean_orbit_radius = 11,483,000 km<ref name="ScottSS" /> | surface_area = | volume = | density = | mass = | surface_grav = <!--Equatorial surface gravity--> | moment_of_inertia_factor = | escape_velocity = | albedo = | single_temperature = }} '''Jupiter LXXI''', originally known as '''S/2018 J 1''', is an outer [[natural satellite]] of [[Jupiter]]. It was discovered by [[Scott S. Sheppard]] and his team in 2018, and was announced on July 17, 2018, via a [[Minor Planet Electronic Circular]] from the [[Minor Planet Center]].<ref name="mpec">{{cite web|title=MPEC 2018-O18 : S/2018 J 1|url=https://minorplanetcenter.net/mpec/K18/K18O18.html|website=Minor Planet Center|publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]]|accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref> It is about {{convert|3|km|sigfig=1}} in diameter and has an orbit radius of around {{convert|11483000|km|mi|abbr=off}}; its [[orbital inclination]] is about 30.61°.<ref name="ScottSS">{{cite web |last1=Sheppard |first1=Scott S. |title=JupiterMoons |url=https://sites.google.com/carnegiescience.edu/sheppard/moons/jupitermoons |website=carnegiescience.edu |publisher=sites.google.com |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> It belongs to the [[Himalia group]].
