{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}} [[File:Cordulagomphus 01.JPG|thumb|right|''[[Cordulagomphus]]'', a [[dragonfly]] from the [[Cretaceous]]]] '''Prehistoric insects''' are various groups of [[insect]]s that lived before [[recorded history]]. Their study is the field of [[paleoentomology]]. Insects inhabited [[Earth]] since before the time of the [[dinosaur]]s. The earliest identifiable insect is the [[Devonian]] ''[[Rhyniognatha hirsti]]'', estimated at {{Ma|407|396}}. Forms similar to many modern insects had already evolved before the dawning of the dinosaur and lived alongside them and beyond up to the present day. Like today, prehistoric insects were an important part of the [[food chain]] in their time.
The differences between modern and prehistoric varieties can be essential, and, like many other creatures of prehistory, the latter tended to be much larger than their contemporary equivalents. This size difference is thought to be due to higher [[atmospheric]] [[oxygen]] levels (allowing [[diffusion]] through [[spiracle]]s over greater distances), higher [[temperature]]s (enhancing [[metabolism]]), and the absence of birds as key [[Predation|predators]] of insect life.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-04/giant-prehistoric-insects-shrank-to-escape-developing-birds.html Giant prehistoric insects shrank to escape developing birds, Bloomberg News, 4 June 2012]</ref>
Since insects have [[chitin]] [[exoskeleton]]s rather than [[mineral]]ized [[bone]]s, their [[taphonomy|burial]] processes differ compared to the [[fossil]]s of much larger [[vertebrate]]s such as [[dinosaur]]s. Many insect remains are found preserved in the hardened [[Sap (plant)|sap]] of ancient [[tree]]s ([[amber]]). [[File:Baltic amber Coleoptera Brentidae Apion 3.JPG|thumb|right|A [[weevil]] caught in [[Baltic amber]]]]
Incomplete list of prehistoric insects arranged by extinction date:
